"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723741","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-26","<p>The Office for National Statistics (ONS) produces comparisons of UK productivity with the G7 countries and some, but not all, EU member states. ONS statistics show output per hour worked in the UK was 15.9% below the average for the rest of the G7 advanced economies in 2015; 22.7% below that in France; 26.7% below Germany and 22.2% below the USA.</p><p>Please see attached tables for full details.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-04-26T13:40:47.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723741/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723741/answer","productivity-tables-HL6783.pdf","productivity-tables-HL6783.pdf","Productivity statistics","Productivity statistics","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723741/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-24","Productivity","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the productivity of UK workers in comparison with workers in (1) other EU member states, and (2) the US.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kennedy of Cradley",,"Baroness Kennedy of Cradley","HL6783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723742","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","true","2017-04-27","<p><del class="ministerial"><em>It has not proved possible to respond to this question in the time available before Prorogation. Ministers will correspond directly with the Member.</em></del></p><p><ins class="ministerial">Brand names can be used but this must be done in line with the Food Information for Consumers Regulation (EU) 1169/2011 which prohibits food labelling from misleading the consumer. The way that product brands influence consumers’ choices will vary between cases, depending on the circumstances. Enforcement authorities will take action if there is evidence that a food business operator is labelling food in a way that is misleading.</ins></p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-04-27T10:58:14.467Z","2017-04-27T15:06:56.36Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723742/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723742/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723742/answer",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723742/answer/previousversion/46575","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-24","Supermarkets: Marketing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what evidence they have that UK supermarkets sell products using the names of non-existent farms and other businesses.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL6784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723743","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-26","<p>The effectiveness of the Groceries Code is being assessed as part of the on-going Statutory Review of the Groceries Code Adjudicator which will be published in due course.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-04-26T13:40:05.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723743/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723743/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723743/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-24","Supermarkets: Codes of Practice","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the effectiveness of the Groceries Code.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL6785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723744","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-27","<p>​Boko Haram have committed horrendous atrocities against communities in Nigeria and the wider region. We estimate that over 20,000 people have been killed by the group. The Nigerian armed forces have severely weakened Boko Haram, but the group remains a threat to security in the region. We remain committed to supporting Nigeria and its neighbours in the fight against Boko Haram and are providing a package of military and intelligence support.</p><p>We are also concerned by credible reports of human rights violations by the Nigerian security forces and the accidental bombing by the Nigerian Air Force in January of a camp for displaced people in Rann. We continually make clear to the Nigerian authorities the importance of upholding human rights standards for all, including protecting civilians in conflict areas and detention. The military support that we are providing is designed not only to counter terrorism, but also to improve human rights standards.</p><p>We welcome President Buhari's commitment to improve the human rights situation, for example, his commitment to overhaul the Nigerian armed force's rules of engagement and to ensure that human rights violations by the security forces are investigated and appropriate action is taken. We also welcome the news that the Nigerian Air Force has launched an investigation into the tragic incident in Rann. Nevertheless, despite these positive steps, more needs to be done. We continue to work with the Nigerian government, non-governmental organisations and civil society to improve the security situation and human rights for all in Nigeria.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-04-27T12:12:22.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723744/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723744/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723744/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-24","Nigeria: Human Rights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their latest assessment of the human rights situation in Nigeria.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL6786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723745","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-27","<p>We are deeply concerned by recent developments relating to the Baha’i community in Yemen. The Houthis and all parties in Yemen must respect the freedom of religion and the rights of all Yemenis.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-04-27T12:01:15.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723745/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723745/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723745/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-24","Yemen: Human Rights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their latest assessment of the human rights situation in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL6787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723746","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-27","<p>Despite considerable progress towards improving the rule of law in Burma in recent years, we remain deeply concerned about ongoing human rights violations by the military in Burma. These include violations of civil and political rights, conflict-related violations including sexual violence, and widespread and systematic discrimination against Muslims in Rakhine State. I raised concerns with the Burmese authorities about a range of human rights issues when I visited in November with a focus on conflict related sexual abuses and Rakhine. The Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Johnson) made representations at the highest levels to both the civilian and military administration when he visited in January. In addition to political advocacy, the UK co-sponsored a Resolution at the Human Rights Council in March raising international concerns and mandating a UN Fact Finding Mission to look into the recent reports of widespread human rights violations in Rakhine State. We also fund project work through NGOs in Burma that provide practical support to promote human rights on the ground.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-04-27T12:20:59.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723746/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723746/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723746/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-24","Burma: Human Rights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their latest assessment of the human rights situation in Myanmar.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL6788"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723747","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-27","<p>​The human rights situation in Somalia continues to be blighted by serious violations and abuses perpetrated by state and non state actors. A 2016/2017 electoral process resulted in a peaceful transfer of power, and increased representation of women in parliament. However, there were increased Al Shabaab attacks in the electoral period, including against civilians. 2016 saw a marked increase in the number of children involved in armed conflict, and frequent reports of civilian casualties in armed conflict. Sexual violence remains endemic. Access to justice remains very restricted. The Committee to Protect Journalists' annual Impunity Index named Somalia, for the second time in 2016, as the worst place in the world to be a journalist. The death penalty continues to be applied and carried out.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-04-27T12:21:49.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723747/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723747/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723747/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-24","Somalia: Human Rights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their latest assessment of the human rights situation in Somalia.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL6789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723748","Department of Health","false","2017-04-27","<p>There are 361 non-medical directors employed by either foundation or non-foundation National Health Service hospital trusts who earned more than £142,500, the prime minister’s salary in 2015, in the 12 months to the end of December 2016. The data produced by NHS Digital is based on total earnings which is basic salary plus any additional payments.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England employs 17 non-medical directors who earn more than £142,500 and the data produced by NHS England is based on basic pay and has been adjusted for part-time hours.</p><p> </p><p>The term non-medical directors has been defined as those having a job role as a director or chief executive and does not include non-executive directors, medical directors or those staff with a medical occupation code.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-04-27T11:59:38.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723748/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723748/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723748/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-24","NHS: Directors","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many non-medical directors employed in NHS Hospital Trusts and NHS England earn more than the Prime Minister.","false","Biography information for Baroness McIntosh of Hudnall",,"Baroness McIntosh of Hudnall","HL6790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723749","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-27","<p>The Office of the Pubs Code Adjudicator (PCA) is up and running. Tenants are raising issues and queries with the PCA via the helpline and website, and referring cases to him under the Pubs Code. On 21 April 2017, Paul Newby, the PCA, announced the latest figures on completed arbitration cases. The total number of cases in which the Adjudicator has made awards is 25, including the five cases announced on 9 March 2017. The PCA currently has 97 cases at different stages within the arbitration process.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-04-27T11:49:41.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723749/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723749/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723749/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-24","Public Houses","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what progress has been made implementing and enforcing the pubs code.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL6791"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723750","HM Treasury","false","2017-04-26","<p>Information on the FCA’s enforcement powers and its policy for financial penalty is set out in detail in the enforcement section of their website, and in their Handbook.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA does not seek to agree specific disciplinary action firms should take against individuals. If the FCA thinks that disciplinary action should be taken against individuals, it can and does take that action itself.</p><p> </p><p>We have passed Lord Mendelsohn’s questions on to the FCA, who will reply directly to him by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe","HL6793 ; HL6794 ; HL6795 ; HL6796","2017-04-26T16:12:54.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723750/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723750/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723750/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-04-24","Financial Services: Fines","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, for each fine imposed by the Financial Conduct Authority since 2007, what was (1) the amount of the fine before any discounts arising from early settlement, (2) the amount paid, and (3) the amount of any discounts applied.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL6792"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723751","HM Treasury","false","2017-04-26","<p>Information on the FCA’s enforcement powers and its policy for financial penalty is set out in detail in the enforcement section of their website, and in their Handbook.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA does not seek to agree specific disciplinary action firms should take against individuals. If the FCA thinks that disciplinary action should be taken against individuals, it can and does take that action itself.</p><p> </p><p>We have passed Lord Mendelsohn’s questions on to the FCA, who will reply directly to him by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe","HL6792 ; HL6794 ; HL6795 ; HL6796","2017-04-26T16:12:54.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723751/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723751/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723751/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-04-24","Financial Services: Fines","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government on how many occasions the Financial Conduct Authority has exercised its powers to increase a fine that it has already imposed; and, in each case, what were the reasons for the exercise of those powers.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL6793"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723752","HM Treasury","false","2017-04-26","<p>Information on the FCA’s enforcement powers and its policy for financial penalty is set out in detail in the enforcement section of their website, and in their Handbook.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA does not seek to agree specific disciplinary action firms should take against individuals. If the FCA thinks that disciplinary action should be taken against individuals, it can and does take that action itself.</p><p> </p><p>We have passed Lord Mendelsohn’s questions on to the FCA, who will reply directly to him by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe","HL6792 ; HL6793 ; HL6795 ; HL6796","2017-04-26T16:12:54.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723752/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723752/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723752/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-04-24","Financial Services: Fines","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what are all the factors they, and the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), consider as aggravating a breach of conduct for which a fine may be imposed by the FCA, which may lead to an increase in that fine.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL6794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723753","HM Treasury","false","2017-04-26","<p>Information on the FCA’s enforcement powers and its policy for financial penalty is set out in detail in the enforcement section of their website, and in their Handbook.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA does not seek to agree specific disciplinary action firms should take against individuals. If the FCA thinks that disciplinary action should be taken against individuals, it can and does take that action itself.</p><p> </p><p>We have passed Lord Mendelsohn’s questions on to the FCA, who will reply directly to him by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe","HL6792 ; HL6793 ; HL6794 ; HL6796","2017-04-26T16:12:54.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723753/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723753/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723753/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-04-24","Financial Services: Fines","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how the Financial Conduct Authority investigates and documents the process by which it evaluates aggravating factors which may lead to an increase in an already imposed fine.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL6795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723754","HM Treasury","false","2017-04-26","<p>Information on the FCA’s enforcement powers and its policy for financial penalty is set out in detail in the enforcement section of their website, and in their Handbook.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA does not seek to agree specific disciplinary action firms should take against individuals. If the FCA thinks that disciplinary action should be taken against individuals, it can and does take that action itself.</p><p> </p><p>We have passed Lord Mendelsohn’s questions on to the FCA, who will reply directly to him by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe","HL6792 ; HL6793 ; HL6794 ; HL6795","2017-04-26T16:12:54.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723754/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723754/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723754/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-04-24","Financial Services: Fines","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government in how many instances since 2007 did the Financial Conduct Authority increase a financial penalty as a result of a firm failing to take disciplinary action against staff; and in each case, what was the reason for the increase.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL6796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723755","HM Treasury","false","2017-04-27","<p>The Government published the Litter Strategy for England on 10 April. The Strategy sets out a range of measures to tackle litter, which includes chewing gum, and littering behaviour.</p><p> </p><p>HM Treasury has not given consideration to the introduction of a tax on chewing gum.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-04-27T10:53:31.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723755/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723755/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723755/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-04-24","Chewing Gum: Taxation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consideration they have given to the introduction of a tax on chewing gum to be used to fund local authority clean-up programmes for discarded gum.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL6797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723756","HM Treasury","false","2017-04-27","<p>The information requested is not available. HM Revenue and Customs do not hold such detailed data on VAT, for example.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-04-27T10:53:50.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723756/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723756/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723756/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-04-24","Motor Vehicles: Taxation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their estimate of the total amount of taxation raised from road users in all forms related to their road use, including through VAT and other duties, in the last financial year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL6798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723757","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-26","<p>In 2016/17, Highways England spent £3.1bn in total in covering construction and maintenance of the Strategic Road Network, and the Traffic Officer Service.</p><p>The Government provided a total of £137.6m to local authorities from the local majors programme for the construction of new local roads.</p><p> </p><p>The Government also allocated £1.029 billion to local authorities for highways maintenance in England outside London This was made up of £826m highways maintenance block needs element, £50m highways maintenance block incentive element, £103m highways maintenance block challenge fund and £50m Pothole Action Fund. A further £258 million was provided to local authorities in England outside London for small scale transport improvements through the integrated transport block.</p><p> </p><p>The Mayor of London receives an annual grant from the Government for transport including rail, underground and roads, so the Department does not hold a breakdown of the expenditure.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-04-26T11:53:20.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723757/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723757/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723757/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-04-24","Roads: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much funding they allocated to (1) the Highways Agency, (2) local authorities, and (3) other bodies, for the construction and maintenance of roads and pavements in the last financial year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL6799"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723758","Home Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>The decision as to whether to carry out a Safeguarding Adult Review is a matter for the relevant Safeguarding Adult Board.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-04-26T16:03:51.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723758/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723758/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723758/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-04-24","Sexual Offences: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to initiate a serious case review into the case of the vulnerable adult who was imprisoned and abused by Keith and Caroline Baker.","false","Biography information for Lord Morrow",,"Lord Morrow","HL6800"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723759","Home Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>The government relies on the Advisory Council on the Misuse of Drugs to inform its assessment of drug harms. The most recent advice from the ACMD relating to cannabis is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/acmd-cannabis-classification-and-public-health-2008" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/acmd-cannabis-classification-and-public-health-2008</a></p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-04-26T16:14:38.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723759/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723759/answer","acmd-cannabis-report-2008.pdf","acmd-cannabis-report-2008.pdf","ACMD Report - Cannabis ","ACMD Report - Cannabis ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723759/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-04-24","Cannabis","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have made an assessment of the differing risks posed by different strengths of cannabis; and, if so, whether they have published those results.","false","Biography information for Lord Northbrook",,"Lord Northbrook","HL6801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723760","Department for International Development","false","2017-04-26","<p>The table below shows DFID Bilateral ODA expenditure on HIV/AIDS for the last five years for which figures are available.</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="6"><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>.</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>£</p></td><td><p><em>Thousands</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>.</p></td><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2015</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>STD control including HIV/AIDS</p></td><td><p>183,079</p></td><td><p>115,146</p></td><td><p>56,077</p></td><td><p>25,605</p></td><td><p>16,434</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The majority of our investments to the HIV response are now directed through multilateral partners such as the Global Fund to fight AIDS, TB and Malaria, UNITAID and UNAIDS. This enables us to have greater impact on HIV than we could achieve through bilateral programmes alone.They can deliver the large-scale, low-cost programmes needed in the most effective way and at the best value to the taxpayer. For example, our £1.1billion investment in the Global Fund (2017-19), up from our £1bn pledge in 2014-2016, makes us the second largest donor. This support will help provide lifesaving anti-retroviral therapy for 1.3 million people living with HIV.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-04-26T16:55:07.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723760/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723760/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723760/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-04-24","Developing Countries: HIV Infection","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much the Department for International Development has spent on bilateral funding for HIV and AIDS programmes in each of the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Baroness Sheehan",,"Baroness Sheehan","HL6802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723761","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-04-26","<p>Bereavement Support Payment is intended to help people with the additional costs immediately following a bereavement. Income-related benefits are more suited for longer-term assistance with everyday living expenses. Evidence from the Government’s public consultation exercise in 2011 suggested the financial impact of spousal bereavement was more acute in the early months; and so this new benefit provides a significant cash boost of a lump sum followed by 18 monthly instalments. The Government originally proposed 12 monthly instalments, but in response to representations from the Social Security Advisory Committee, the Work and Pensions Select Committee and groups supporting bereaved people, this was extended to 18 months. This ensures that the payments do not end on the anniversary of the death.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2017-04-26T16:14:16.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723761/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723761/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723761/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-04-24","Bereavement Support Payment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why, when determining the length of time for which Bereavement Support Payments would be paid, they considered 18 months a suitable timeframe for bereavement support.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of St Albans",,"The Lord Bishop of St Albans","HL6803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723762","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-27","<p>The Assessment, Care in Custody and Teamwork (ACCT) process is the multi-disciplinary case management system that is used to provide support for prisoners assessed as being at risk of self-harm or suicide.</p><p> </p><p>We are committed to improving the support that we offer to prisoners at risk. We expect the most important and effective measures to be the recruitment of 2,500 new staff, and the introduction of new offender management arrangements in prisons under which each key worker will have particular responsibility for a small number of prisoners. These will greatly enhance the time and resources available to support prisoners who are at risk.</p><p> </p><p>We continue to work in partnership with the Samaritans to provide the Listener scheme, through which volunteer prisoners are trained to provide support to other prisoners in emotional distress. Additional grant funding for the Samaritans in 2017-18 will facilitate a number of improvements to that scheme and some other initiatives, including a pilot project to provide training on building emotional resilience for prisoners in their early days in custody, to be delivered by released ex-Listeners.</p><p> </p><p>Other measures are being developed as part of our safety programme, which includes specific strands of work on the early days in custody, the case management of prisoners at risk, and building hopefulness amongst prisoners, including through family and peer support.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-04-27T14:29:44.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723762/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723762/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723762/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-04-24","Prisoners: Suicide","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Keen of Elie on 3 April (HL6247), what are the measures that will be put in place to help support prisoners who are at risk of self-harm or suicide.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of St Albans",,"The Lord Bishop of St Albans","HL6804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723763","HM Treasury","false","2017-04-27","<p>The Common Reporting Standard (CRS) is the global standard for the exchange of financial account information and any changes would need to be agreed internationally. Under the CRS financial institutions, including some charities, are required to obtain and report tax residence information of their account holders. The information that tax authorities will receive under the CRS, including that on distributions from charities, is a vital part of global efforts to tackle offshore tax evasion and increase tax transparency.</p><p> </p><p>Consistent implementation of the CRS by all adopting jurisdictions is important to create a level playing field and to ensure that avoidance loopholes are not created.</p><p> </p><p>Officials in HM Revenue and Customs are working closely with charity sector representatives to minimise the compliance burden.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-04-27T10:54:31.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723763/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723763/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723763/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-04-24","Charities: Taxation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to review the application of the Common Reporting Standard to small charities, including Parochial Church Councils, that are currently obliged to complete Tax Jurisdiction Entity Certification in the same manner as financial institutions, in the light of the considerable cost of doing so, and of the lack of any <i>de minimis</i> exemption for small donations; and if so, when.","false","Biography information for Lord Vinson",,"Lord Vinson","HL6805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723764","Department for Transport","false","2017-04-26","<p>The roadworks underway on the M3 between junctions 2 (the M25) and 4a near Fleet services) consist of two combined schemes (a Smart Motorway scheme and a maintenance scheme). These have been underway for 26 months, and are currently due to finish construction in two months in June 2017. The cost estimate approved for these works was £256 million. The current estimated outturn cost of the scheme is also £256 million.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-04-26T11:53:54.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723764/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723764/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723764/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-04-24","M3","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government for how many months roadworks have been underway on the M3 motorway between the Fleet Services and the M25; for how many months those roadworks are expected to continue; what was the initial cost estimate for those works; and what is the current estimated cost.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL6806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723765","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-27","<p>Syria Civil Defence (SCD), also known as the White Helmets, plays an invaluable role in rescuing people from the devastation caused by Syrian and Russian air and missile strikes. The 107 SCD teams, of over 3100 volunteer women and men, deliver community-based services to approximately four million Syrian civilians living in opposition-controlled areas. To date they have saved over 85,000 lives and conducted extensive mine risk awareness campaigns to help civilians protect themselves from unexploded ordnance. 167 SCD volunteers have been killed and another 480 seriously injured while carrying out their life-saving work.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-04-27T12:20:19.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723765/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723765/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723765/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-24","White Helmets","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the value of the White Helmets in humanitarian work in the Syrian conflict.","false","Biography information for Lord Eames",,"Lord Eames","HL6807"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723766","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-27","<p>Syria Civil Defence is funded by a group of Western nations, including the UK. We have provided almost £30 million since we first began work with SCD in 2013, including contributions of around £11 million in 2015-16 and around £11 million in 2016-17. HMG will contribute a further £8.2 million in 2017-18. The United States, Canada, Germany, the Netherlands and Denmark also provide funding to SCD.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-04-27T12:20:33.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723766/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723766/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723766/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-24","White Helmets","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much financial assistance was provided by the UK to the White Helmets in (1) 2015–16, and (2) the current year to date.","false","Biography information for Lord Eames",,"Lord Eames","HL6808"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723767","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-27","<p>Her Majesty's Government monitors the work of the Syria Civil Defence (SCD) through frequent contact with our implementing partner and receives regular reporting including specific incident reports, weekly reports, and quarterly project reports. The activities of SCD are also monitored and evaluated by our implementing partner; through independent audits; and through third party monitoring. These reports and continuing monitoring contribute to HMG's work to ensure due diligence, evaluation and accountability for project delivery.</p><p>HMG is not aware of reported attacks on civilians by the White Helmets. While all allegations of human rights abuses are treated seriously, HMG notes that the Syrian regime and Russia sought to discredit Syria Civil Defence through a concerted disinformation campaign. HMG remains steadfast in our support to the 3100 women and men of Syria Civil Defence who continue to risk their lives to save lives and make their communities more resilient.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-04-27T12:18:57.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723767/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723767/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723767/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-24","White Helmets","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how the activities of the White Helmets in Syria are observed and analysed; and by whom.","false","Biography information for Lord Eames",,"Lord Eames","HL6809"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723768","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-27","<p>Her Majesty's Government (HMG) monitors the work of the Syria Civil Defence (SCD) through frequent contact with our implementing partner. We receive regular reporting, including specific incident reports, weekly reports, and quarterly project reports. The activities of SCD are also monitored and evaluated by our implementing partner; through independent audits; and through third party monitoring. These reports and continuing monitoring contribute to HMG's work to ensure due diligence, evaluation and accountability for project delivery.</p><p>HMG is not aware of reported attacks on civilians by the White Helmets. While all allegations of human rights abuses are treated seriously, HMG notes that the Syrian regime and Russia have sought to discredit Syria Civil Defence through a concerted disinformation campaign. HMG remains steadfast in our support to the 3100 women and men of Syria Civil Defence who continue to risk their lives to save others.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-04-27T12:18:42.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723768/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723768/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723768/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-24","White Helmets","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what reports they have received on the activities of the White Helmets in Syria; what are the sources of such reports; and what action was taken as a result.","false","Biography information for Lord Eames",,"Lord Eames","HL6810"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723769","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-27","<p>Her Majesty's Government (HMG) is not aware of reported attacks on civilians by the White Helmets. While all allegations of human rights abuses are treated seriously, HMG notes that the Syrian regime and Russia sought to discredit Syria Civil Defence (SCD) through a concerted disinformation campaign. HMG remains steadfast in our support to the 3100 women and men of Syria Civil Defence who continue to risk their lives to save lives and make their communities more resilient.</p><p>HMG monitors the work of SCD through frequent contact with our implementing partner and receives regular reporting including specific incident reports, weekly reports, and quarterly project reports. The activities of SCD are also monitored and evaluated by our implementing partner; through independent audits; and through third party monitoring. These reports and continuing monitoring contribute to HMG's work to ensure due diligence, evaluation and accountability for project delivery.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-04-27T12:14:45.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723769/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723769/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723769/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-24","White Helmets","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of reported attacks on civilians in Syria by the White Helmets.","false","Biography information for Lord Eames",,"Lord Eames","HL6811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723770","Department for International Development","false","2017-04-26","<p>The Department for International Development (DFID) leads the UK's humanitarian response to the Syria crisis. It is our largest ever response to a single humanitarian crisis. We are providing lifesaving support to millions of Syrians, supporting Syrians who have fled as refugees to neighbouring countries, and enabling host communities to accommodate them.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-04-26T16:46:36.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723770/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723770/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723770/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-04-24","Syria: Humanitarian Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government which department is responsible for the allocation of humanitarian aid to Syria.","false","Biography information for Lord Eames",,"Lord Eames","HL6812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723771","Home Office","false","2017-04-27","<p>I am sorry but the information is not held in the format requested.</p><p>The available information on the number of applications for visas for study using sponsor acceptances, by country of nationality, and corresponding information for applicants sponsored by UK-based Higher Education Institutions, is published in the quarterly Immigration Statistics, Sponsorship tables cs_11, cs_11_q, cs_13 and cs_13_q. The latest edition is available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-october-to-december-2016/list-of-tables#sponsorship" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-october-to-december-2016/list-of-tables#sponsorship</a></p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-04-27T10:59:25.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723771/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723771/answer","Sponsorship Tables cs_11-cs11q_cs13 and c13q.xlsx","Sponsorship Tables cs_11-cs11q_cs13 and c13q.xlsx","Sponsorship Tables - cs11, cs_11, c_13 and cs13q ","Sponsorship Tables - cs11, cs_11, c_13 and cs13q ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723771/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-04-24","Entry Clearances: India","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford (HL6314), how many Indian nationals were applicants for (1) visas for study using sponsor acceptances, and (2) visas for study at UK-based Higher Education Institutions, in each year from 2005 to 2010.","false","Biography information for Lord Green of Deddington",,"Lord Green of Deddington","HL6813"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723772","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-27","<p>We strongly condemn the recent attacks in Egypt against the Coptic Christian community, claimed by Daesh. The Government of Egypt has reaffirmed its commitment to protecting the rights of minorities and to the need to promote religious tolerance. We welcome President Sisi's calls for peaceful coexistence and the Government of Egypt's expression of support for the rights of Christians and for religious tolerance.</p><p>The UK Government continues to work closely with the Egyptian authorities on security and counter-terrorism.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-04-27T12:11:33.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723772/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723772/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723772/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-24","Egypt: Christianity","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Egypt regarding the bombings of the Coptic churches in Alexandria and Tanta in April.","false","Biography information for Baroness Berridge",,"Baroness Berridge","HL6814"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723773","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-27","<p>​We strongly condemn the recent attacks on the Coptic Christian community in Egypt, claimed by Daesh. Her Majesty's ambassador to Egypt, John Casson, met Pope Tawadros II on 22 April and offered his condolences. I regularly meet Bishop Angaelos, Bishop of the Coptic Orthodox Church in the UK, and passed on my sincere condolences following the abhorrent recent attacks. The British Government is committed to working with international partners, including Egypt, to strengthen the protection of freedom of religion or belief.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-04-27T12:21:26.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723773/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723773/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723773/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-24","Egypt: Christianity","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions, or meetings, they have had with (1) Pope Tawadros II of Alexandria, and (2) the leadership of the Coptic Church in the UK, regarding the bombings of the Coptic churches in Alexandria and Tanta in April.","false","Biography information for Baroness Berridge",,"Baroness Berridge","HL6815"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723774","Department of Health","false","2017-04-27","<p>The practise of chiropody is regulated by the Health and Care Professionals Council (HCPC). Anyone wanting to use the title of chiropodist must be registered with the HCPC. A person who is not registered and either misuses the title, claims they are registered or claims they have chiropody qualifications, whether expressly or by implication, is committing an offence.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-04-27T11:58:38.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723774/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723774/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723774/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-24","Podiatry","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to regulate the use of the description chiropodist in relation to the advertising of services to the public.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradley",,"Lord Bradley","HL6816"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723775","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","true","2017-04-27","<p><del class="ministerial"><em>It has not proved possible to respond to this question in the time available before Prorogation. Ministers will correspond directly with the Member.</em></del></p><p><ins class="ministerial">Fly-tipping is unacceptable whether it occurs on public or private land. Not only does it blight the areas in which it occurs but may also pose a risk to the environment and human health.</ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial"> </ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial">In May 2016 we gave local councils the power to issue fixed penalty notices of up to £400 for small-scale fly-tipping as an alternative to more costly prosecutions. This built on other action to tackle fly-tipping, including: working with the sentencing Council on its sentencing guideline for environmental offences; making it easier for vehicles suspected of being involved in waste crime to be stopped, searched and seized; continuing to chair the National Fly-Tipping Prevention Group to promote and disseminate good practice for tackling fly-tipping; strengthening the waste Duty of Care by publishing a revised Code of Practice and supporting the industry-led Right Waste Right Place campaign to promote Duty of Care to small businesses.</ins></p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-04-27T10:57:54.903Z","2017-04-27T15:06:17.85Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723775/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723775/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723775/answer",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723775/answer/previousversion/46577","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-24","Fly-tipping","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what proposals they have to reduce the amount of fly tipping in the UK; and when any such proposals will be introduced.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL6817"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723776","Home Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>The Home Office first published information on police outcomes for domestic abuse-related offences in ‘Crime outcomes in England and Wales: year ending March 2016’, available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/crime-outcomes-in-england-and-wales-2015-to-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/crime-outcomes-in-england-and-wales-2015-to-2016</a>.</p><p> </p><p>As this was the first time police forces were required to collect figures in this way it is not possible to compare them to earlier years.</p><p> </p><p>The Office of National Statistics has been clear that recent rises in recorded crime reflect improved processes and a greater willingness of victims to come forward there are too many instances where victims are unwilling to testify against their abuser. The Government expects police forces and Crown Prosecutors to use the available data, alongside local knowledge, to review performance in relation to domestic abuse in order to identify areas for improvement.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-04-26T16:08:19.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723776/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723776/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723776/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-04-24","Domestic Abuse","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of figures released following a freedom of information request showing that more than 160,000 victims of domestic violence in England withdrew their support for charges against their abusers in 2016, what percentage rise this represents compared with the previous 12 months; and what assessment they have made of the factors which led to those withdrawals.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL6818"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723777","Department for Education","false","2017-04-26","<p>As an independent statutory body responsible for enforcing the Equality Act 2010, the EHRC is able to make its own decisions to intervene if it suspects that an unlawful act has been committed. It has the power to take enforcement action in relation to a breach of the Act’s provisions, including the provisions that cover appointment to public office.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-04-26T16:06:54.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723777/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723777/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723777/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-24","Channel Four Television: Public Appointments","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ashton of Hyde on 20 April (HL6668) concerning the female candidate who was not approved for appointment by the Secretary of State to the Board of Channel 4, whether they intend to ask the Equalities and Human Rights Commission to examine the appointments process, with respect to the question of whether race or gender discrimination were factors in the decision made.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL6819"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723778","Department for Education","false","2017-04-26","<p>Statistics on truancy for 2014 and 2015 (latest currently available) are published by the Ministry of Justice in the “Criminal justice statistics outcomes by offence data tool”, available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/criminal-justice-system-statistics-quarterly-december-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/criminal-justice-system-statistics-quarterly-december-2015</a>. Figures for 2016 are not yet available.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Criminal Justice Statistics outcome for truancy offences, 2014 to 2015</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of defendants proceeded against</p></td><td><p>17,013</p></td><td><p>20,808</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The Government has been clear that children’s attendance at school is non-negotiable. It is for schools to determine how they address poor attendance using the range of measures available to them, such as parenting contracts and parenting orders, or penalty notice for unauthorised absence. These measures are used to reinforce parents’ responsibilities and to support them in improving their child’s attendance at school.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-04-26T16:09:29.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723778/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723778/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723778/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-24","Truancy","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many parents were prosecuted in relation to truancy by their children in (1) 2014, (2) 2015, and (3) 2016; and what measures they are proposing to take to reduce the levels of school absence.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL6820"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723779","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-26","<p>It has not proved possible to respond to this question in the time available before Prorogation. Ministers will correspond directly with the Member.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-04-26T11:17:59.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723779/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723779/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723779/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-24","Homelessness","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what progress they are making in reducing the levels of homelessness among single young people and families living in temporary accommodation; and what assessment they have made of the need to increase the provision of (1) affordable accommodation, and (2) private rented accommodation at rent levels proportionate to household incomes.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL6821"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723780","Department for Education","false","2017-04-26","<p>Local authorities and schools seek consent from the Secretary of State to dispose of playing field land that is surplus or unused. The department has a strong policy presumption against the disposal of school playing fields and has a set of criteria used to assess applications for consent. These include assessing whether the school can continue to meet its curriculum needs. The department gives consent only if the criteria are met, and where the proceeds from sales are to be reinvested in sports and education facilities.</p><p>PE remains a compulsory subject at all four key stages in the national curriculum, ensuring that all children and young people continue to engage in sport and physical activity as they progress through education and beyond. Schools are free to organise and deliver a diverse and challenging PE curriculum, but through the primary PE and sport premium. The government has invested over £600m of ring-fenced funding to primary schools to improve PE and sport since 2013, and will double the primary PE and sport premium to £320 million a year from September 2017. We also recently announced the creation of the Healthy Pupils Capital Programme, committing £415m of additional funding from the Soft Drinks Industry Levy for primary, secondary, and sixth form colleges to support PE, after school activities, healthy eating, and young people suffering with mental health issues.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-04-26T16:12:06.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723780/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723780/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723780/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-24","Playgrounds","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the impact of the closure of children’s playgrounds on the health, security, safety and education of children.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL6822"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723781","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-27","<p>The UK is in regular discussion with Israel, the Palestinian Authority (PA), the UN and the EU about Gaza’s energy crisis. We are not aware of a decrease in electricity supply from Israel. However we regularly call on both Israel and the PA to swiftly implement key infrastructure projects that will increase the electricity supply to Gaza.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-04-27T12:24:59.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723781/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723781/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723781/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-24","Gaza: Electricity","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they are making to the government of Israel and the UN concerning the restoration of electricity supplies to Gaza.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL6823"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723782","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-27","<p>​While we have not raised this specific issue with the Israeli authorities, we have repeatedly raised our concerns about incidents of settler violence and intimidation, and have stressed the importance of thorough investigations and accountability.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-04-27T12:12:56.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723782/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723782/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723782/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-24","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they are making to the government of Israel regarding reports of the desecration of Islamic sites in the occupied Palestinian territories by Israeli settlers, during the Jewish Passover holiday.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL6824"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723783","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-27","<p>​We have not made recent representations to the government of Israel on this issue. We note Israel’s recent commitment that prisoners and detainees are treated humanely and in accordance with international law.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-04-27T12:18:14.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723783/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723783/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723783/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-24","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they are making to the government of Israel regarding the conditions for Palestinian prisoners in Israeli jails.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL6825"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723784","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-27","<p>While we have not raised this issue with the Israeli authorities, the UK has repeatedly made clear to Israel our longstanding concerns about the manner in which the Israel Defence Forces polices non-violent protests and the border areas, including use of lethal and non-lethal ammunition.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-04-27T12:09:32.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723784/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723784/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723784/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-24","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they are making to the government of Israel following the shooting by Israeli police officers of the activist Muhammad Amira.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL6826"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723785","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-27","<p>Our Embassy in Tel Aviv provided consular assistance to Mr Hawwash when he was denied entry to Israel and the Occupied Palestinian territories on 7 April. We will continue press for clarification from the Israeli Ministry of Foreign Affairs on the implications of the law. The UK is strongly opposed to the Boycotts, Divestment and Sanctions Movement against Israel. But we believe the best way to combat this movement is through discussion rather than legislation. Ultimately it is for Israel to decide its immigration policy.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-04-27T12:08:43.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723785/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723785/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723785/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-24","Kemal Hawwash","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what support they are giving to Professor Kemal Hawwash of Birmingham University who has been denied access to both Israel and the Occupied Palestinian territories and is unable to visit his family.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL6827"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723786","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-27","<p>​While we have not raised this issue with the Israeli authorities, the British Government has made clear to the Government of Israel our concerns about the humanitarian and environmental impact of the damage to water sources and the destruction of Palestinian agricultural land that has been caused by settlement-related building activity. We deplore the destruction of Palestinian property and have called on the Israeli Government to cease such activity.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-04-27T12:06:46.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723786/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723786/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723786/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-24","Israeli Settlements","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Israel regarding the reported piping of sewage by Israeli settlers from Carmel, onto the land of Umm Al Kheir.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL6828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723793","Cabinet Office","false","2017-04-27","<p>The information requested is not held.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-04-27T10:12:53.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723793/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723793/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723793/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-04-24","Cabinet Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many officials of his Department have applied for special leave to carry out work for non-government departments in the last nine months.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","71770"
