"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723810","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-27","<p>No such assessment has been made. The legal requirements around the television licence are set out in the Communications Act 2003 and the Communications (Television Licensing) Regulations 2004/692. Further details can be found via http://www.tvlicensing.co.uk/</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-04-27T07:28:47.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723810/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723810/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723810/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-04-24","Television: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether she has made an assessment of the potential merits of ceasing the requirement for those serving in the military to hold a television licence at both their home and base addresses.","false","Biography information for Johnny Mercer","Plymouth, Moor View","Johnny Mercer","71753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723811","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-27","<p>Life Charity submitted a project proposal to support vulnerable women in west London, requesting £250,000. Life Charity’s bid described a project that would help vulnerable, homeless or at risk women (for example, those escaping abuse or trafficking) who are pregnant and have nowhere to turn.</p><p>We will shortly agree the specifics of each of the 70 projects that successfully applied to the Tampon Tax Fund this year, to ensure that taxpayers' money is put to the best use. We will only make grants where we are 100% certain that they align with the aims of the fund.</p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2017-04-27T08:03:26.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723811/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723811/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723811/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-04-24","LIFE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, for what reasons £250 million was provided from the Tampon Tax Fund for the Life charity; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","71725"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723812","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-26","<p>The Tampon Tax Fund aims to support projects that improve the lives of disadvantaged women and girls across the UK. It is not designed to specifically address period poverty.</p><p> </p><p>We will shortly agree the specifics of each of the 70 projects that successfully applied to the Tampon Tax Fund this year, to ensure that taxpayers' money is put to the best use. We will only make grants where we are 100% certain that they align with the aims of the fund.</p><p> </p><p>All applications into the fund were assessed by officials against three criteria: evidence for the need of the project: the organisation’s ability to deliver; and the sustainability/impact of the project, and were then vetted by officials before they were signed off.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2017-04-26T14:38:39.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723812/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723812/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723812/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-04-24","Sanitary Protection: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how the Tampon Tax Fund will address period poverty; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","71708"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723813","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-27","<p>We will shortly finalise the specifics of the grant agreements for each of the 70 projects that successfully applied to the Tampon Tax Fund this year, to ensure that taxpayers' money is put to the best use. We will only make grants where we are 100% certain that they align fully with the aims of the fund. The final decision will be made by the Minister for Civil Society.</p><p> </p><p>All applications into the fund were assessed by officials against three criteria: evidence for the need of the project: the organisation’s ability to deliver; and the sustainability/impact of the project, and were then vetted by officials before they were signed off.</p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2017-04-27T08:07:12.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723813/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723813/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723813/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-04-24","LIFE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 20 April 2017 to Question HL6582, whether the Minister for Civil Society or another Minister made the decision to award the charity Life £250,000 from the Tampon Tax Fund; what her Department's scrutiny process for that decision was; and what representations she received on the appropriateness of that award before that decision was announced.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","71768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723814","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-27","<p>There are no plans to name a RAF Typhoon aircraft &quot;<em>MacRobert's Spirit</em>&quot; as part of the 100th anniversary commemorations of the RAF.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-27T08:12:00.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723814/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723814/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723814/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-24","Air Force: Anniversaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 20 April 2017 to Question 70282, if he will take steps as part of the 100th anniversary commemorations of the RAF to arrange for the name MacRobert's Spirit to be given to a Typhoon fighter aircraft.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","71690"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723815","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-27","<p>There are 229 Service Family Accommodation properties at Gamecock Barracks, of which 201 are occupied, and 497 Single Living Accommodation beds, of which 369 are occupied.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-27T08:08:39.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723815/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723815/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723815/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-24","Gamecock Barracks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the current number of (a) family houses and (b) single living accommodation is at Gamecock Barracks, Nuneaton; and what proportion of that accommodation is occupied.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","71758"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723816","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-27","<p>The infrastructure costs for 34 Field Hospital are not held separately. The cost of infrastructure upgrades at Queen Elizabeth Barracks, Strensall for the financial years (FY) available are set out below:</p><p>FY 2014-15 £0.7 million[1]</p><p>FY 2013-14 £0.8 million</p><p>FY 2012-13 £0.8 million</p><p>[1] Estimated due to lack of access to legacy systems.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-27T08:09:33.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723816/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723816/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723816/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-24","Armed Forces: Hospitals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the cost to the public purse has been of upgrades to 34 Field Hospital in the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","71759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723817","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-27","<p>Building 140 on Imphal Barracks has been demolished. It was an unused building prior to demolition, with no requirement for it to be refurbished, and it was therefore more cost effective to knock it down.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-27T08:08:04.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723817/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723817/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723817/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-24","Imphal Barracks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the current status of Building 140 on Imphal Barracks is.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","71760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723818","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-27","<p>The Department's intention to close Imphal Barracks in 2031 and Towthorpe Lines and Queen Elizabeth Barracks in 2021 forms part of a strategy to optimise the defence estate to better support our Armed Forces.</p><p>Equality Impact Assessments are carried out to ensure suitable and appropriate reprovisions are made when sites are actually closed. Therefore, the Equality Impact Assessment will not be undertaken until much later in the disposals process.</p><p>There are currently no plans to publish the Equality Impact Assessment for military sites in the City of York.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-27T08:07:21.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723818/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723818/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723818/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-24","Military Bases: York","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when he plans to publish an equality impact assessment on the proposal to close military sites in the City of York.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","71761"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723820","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-27","<p>The Ministry of Defence owns approximately 1,722 acres of land in York.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-27T08:05:33.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723820/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723820/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723820/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-24","Ministry of Defence: York","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many acres of land his Department owns in York.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","71762"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723821","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-27","<p>There are no current plans to change the order of battle of the Royal Marines.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-04-27T08:13:20.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723821/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723821/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723821/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-24","Marines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans he has to alter the Order of Battle of the Royal Marines; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","71763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723822","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>​The Counter Proliferation and Arms Control Centre (CPACC) brings together officials from FCO, DIT, MOD and BEIS covering global controls on chemical, biological, nuclear and conventional weapons and on their proliferation. This includes controls on their means of delivery, such as missiles, and broader international work on the security of relevant materials. The Export Control Joint Unit (ECJU) focuses specifically on the control of military and dual use exports, and the operation of the export licensing system. ECJU co-locates DIT’s Export Control Organisation and the export licensing teams from MOD and FCO. Ministerial responsibilities are unchanged.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-04-26T14:46:05.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723822/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723822/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723822/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-24","Counter Proliferation and Arms Control Centre","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will list the responsibilities of the Counter Proliferation and Arms Control Centre; and what the relationship is between that unit and the (a) Export Control Joint Unit and (b) Export Control Organisation.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","71781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723823","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>​Staff from the four departments involved spend all, or part, of their time working as part of the centre. While doing so, they remain employed by the relevant department rather than being seconded to Counter Proliferation and Arms Control Centre (CPACC) or a single department. With the exception of one military officer working in the centre, all staff are drawn from the Civil Service.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-04-26T14:49:03.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723823/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723823/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723823/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-24","Counter Proliferation and Arms Control Centre","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many people currently work within the Counter Proliferation and Arms Control Centre on secondment from (a) other Government Departments and (b) outside the Civil Service.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","71779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723824","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-27","<p>We work very closely with the Home Office, and they have specific rules for Commonwealth personnel in relation to their immigration status while serving and their ability to settle in the UK indefinitely.</p><p>Under the Immigration Act 1971 Commonwealth Nationals are exempt from immigration control whilst serving as a regular in HM Forces. On request, the Home Office will issue Commonwealth personnel an 'Exempt vignette' to confirm their status. This is issued on enlistment, and is valid for the entirety of their regular service and enables them to come and go from the UK without restriction for the purposes of their duty. A wide range of advice and support is available to Service personnel about their immigration status and they will be sign posted to qualified immigration advisers for help with specific questions and applications.</p><p>Service personnel can apply to the Home Office for indefinite leave to remain in the UK up to 10 weeks prior to or, if eligible, within two years of discharge, or indefinite leave to enter the UK within two years of leaving the Services if they have returned to their country of origin. The Home Office determine if they meet the eligibility criteria for settlement.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","71714","2017-04-27T08:06:29.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723824/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723824/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723824/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-24","Fiji: Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what support his Department provides to Fijian citizens in the British Army with Commonwealth passports and indefinite leave to enter or remain in the UK on securing their status and residency rights in the UK.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","71715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723825","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-27","<p>We work very closely with the Home Office, and they have specific rules for Commonwealth personnel in relation to their immigration status while serving and their ability to settle in the UK indefinitely.</p><p>Under the Immigration Act 1971 Commonwealth Nationals are exempt from immigration control whilst serving as a regular in HM Forces. On request, the Home Office will issue Commonwealth personnel an 'Exempt vignette' to confirm their status. This is issued on enlistment, and is valid for the entirety of their regular service and enables them to come and go from the UK without restriction for the purposes of their duty. A wide range of advice and support is available to Service personnel about their immigration status and they will be sign posted to qualified immigration advisers for help with specific questions and applications.</p><p>Service personnel can apply to the Home Office for indefinite leave to remain in the UK up to 10 weeks prior to or, if eligible, within two years of discharge, or indefinite leave to enter the UK within two years of leaving the Services if they have returned to their country of origin. The Home Office determine if they meet the eligibility criteria for settlement.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","71715","2017-04-27T08:06:29.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723825/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723825/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723825/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-24","Fiji: Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what discussions he has had with his Cabinet colleagues on the status and rights of Fijian citizens in the British Army with Commonwealth passports and indefinite leave to enter or remain in the UK to (a) enter UK airports without difficulty and (b) remain in the UK.","false",