"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723110","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-27","<p>As a result of the government's Superfast Broadband Programme and roll-out by the private sector, superfast broadband with speeds of more than 24Mbps is now available to more than 92% of homes and businesses in the UK and the government expects this to reach 95% by the end of 2017. This coverage includes rural areas. The delivery programme in Scotland including the Gordon constituency is delivered by the Scottish Government.</p><p>Thinkbroadband estimate that current coverage of superfast broadband in the Gordon constituency is 79%, which DCMS estimate will rise to 83% by the end of 2017. This compares to a UK average of over 92%. The Scottish Government is responsible for delivering broadband in Scotland.</p><p>Take up in the Rest of Scotland Project area is 28% and as a result of the UK Government's contract management, further funding can be returned to the Scottish Government for reinvestment in more superfast coverage as take-up rises. It would be for the Scottish Government to decide where funding returned by suppliers under the contracts is allocated to increase coverage.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-04-27T14:15:12.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723110/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723110/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723110/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-04-21","Broadband: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps the Government is taking to provide superfast broadband in (a) rural communities and (b) Gordon constituency.","false","Biography information for Alex Salmond","Gordon","Alex Salmond","71659"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723111","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-26","<p>This information is not held centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-04-26T16:59:06.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723111/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723111/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723111/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-04-21","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Capital Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, which capital investment projects have been funded by her Department in each of the last five years; and what the costs of each such project have been.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","71667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723112","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-26","<p>No information is held on the number of contact coupons, also known as &quot;Expressions of Interest&quot; forms, that the Royal Regiment of Scotland has distributed since 2014.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-26T10:30:30.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723112/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723112/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723112/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-21","Royal Regiment of Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many contact coupons were distributed by battalion of the Royal Regiment of Scotland in each year since 2014.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","71545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723113","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-26","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 25 April 2017 to Question 71484.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-04-26T09:37:58.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723113/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723113/answer","Hansard Extract 25 April 2017 HOC 71484.docx","Hansard Extract 25 April 2017 HOC 71484.docx","Aircraft Carriers","Aircraft Carriers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723113/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-21","Amphibious Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans he has to reduce the number of amphibious landing crafts used by the Royal Marines.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","71593"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723114","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-26","<p>British Forces are involved in more than 30 operations in over 20 countries. We are effectively protecting the UK and its interests from a range of threats, and promoting security in key regions of the world.</p><p>Protecting the UK.</p><p>We continue to defend UK airspace with an integrated Air Defence system that includes Quick Reaction Alert Typhoon aircraft held at continuous readiness, Voyager tankers, and air surveillance and control facilities. We also provide such capabilities to police NATO airspace alongside our allies. Royal Navy assets defend our territorial waters and overseas territories, and maintain our Continuous At Sea Deterrent.</p><p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) continues to ensure that the support it provides to the Government response in the event of a UK terrorism incident is in line with the current threat. The MOD has 10,000 military personnel available on standby at short notice to assist the civil authorities for significant terrorist incidents, supported by a wide range of niche military experts and equipment, such as bomb disposal specialists. The Police and maritime authorities have primacy for domestic security of the UK coastline against criminal elements but the MOD maintains forces to provide support to these authorities as required.</p><p>Counter-Daesh, Operation SHADER.</p><p>In Iraq and Syria, Operation SHADER is the UK's military response to the threat posed by Daesh. As part of the Global Coalition, the RAF is conducting airstrikes in support of local forces - the Iraqi Security Forces (including the Kurdish Peshmerga) and the Syrian moderate opposition - who are taking the fight to Daesh. British military training teams are providing highly valuable training to Iraqi forces in infantry skills, counter-IED techniques, medical skills and engineering expertise. This is part of the Government's overall strategy to defeat Daesh which includes stifling Daesh's finances; preventing the flow of foreign terrorist fighters across borders; supporting stabilisation efforts in areas liberated from Daesh; and exposing Daesh's delusional and false-religious narrative through counter-messaging.</p><p>Middle East.</p><p>We continue to underpin our enduring contribution to the security of the Gulf through the deployment of significant maritime and air capabilities. We have further reiterated our commitment to the Gulf States with two recent deployments. The first of these was HMS Daring, which deployed to the Gulf and the Southern Red Sea in October 2016 for seven months, protecting vital shipping lanes and ensuring maritime security. The second was the commitment of the UK's amphibious task group under HMS Ocean, which commanded the regional US-led Coalition Task Force 50 for the first time, from 25 November 2016 to 14 February 2017.</p><p>NATO.</p><p>As part of NATO's enhanced Forward Presence, we have 800 personnel deployed in Estonia and 150 in Poland. We have 30 personnel deployed on NATO's mission in Kosovo and Headquarters Allied Rapid Reaction Corps and the UK Joint Force Air Component are on standby as NATO Response Force (NRF) Component Commands. In addition, we are leading the land element of the Very High Readiness Joint Task Force with 3,000 personnel on standby to deploy rapidly if required. We have deployed Typhoon fast jets to Romania for four months as part of NATO's enhanced Southern Air Policing mission, and we are also contributing Royal Navy warships and Royal Air Force aircraft to the NRF.</p><p>Afghanistan.</p><p>The UK Government continues to make a key contribution to NATO's non-combat train, advise and assist mission which is helping the Afghan National Defence and Security Forces to build security and stability for the long term. The UK has 500 troops in Afghanistan serving in a non-combat role, alongside our NATO partners as advisers in the Afghan security ministries and to the Afghan Air Force, and provide security for NATO Forces in Kabul. As the coalition lead for the Afghan National Army Officer Academy, the UK has helped to train over 2,000 officer cadets, who will be the next generation of military leaders.</p><p>Countering Illegal Migration.</p><p>The Royal Navy has been at the forefront of NATO's activity in the eastern Mediterranean tackling illegal people trafficking and irregular migration in the Aegean Sea. Between March 2016 and January 2017 a Royal Navy or Royal Fleet Auxiliary ship was deployed to the Aegean in support of the Turkish and Greek coastguards. NATO's activity in the Aegean has contributed to a 98% reduction in people attempting to make the dangerous crossing between Turkey and Greece.</p><p>We continue to provide a vessel to the EU's Operation Sophia, which aims to disrupt migrant smuggling in the Mediterranean, and are supporting training of the Libyan coast guard. The UK also has the command of the EU Op Atalanta counter-piracy mission off the Horn of Africa.</p><p>UN Peacekeeping and Training Missions in Africa.</p><p>The UK is increasing its commitment to UN peacekeeping. We have 200 troops on the ground in the UN Mission in South Sudan, set to reach over 350 by May, undertaking vital engineering and medical tasks. Over the last 12 months we have committed up to 70 troops to the UN support mission in Somalia.</p><p>Elsewhere in Africa we have training missions in Nigeria and Somalia, as well as contributing to the EU mission in Mali.</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon",,"2017-04-26T16:07:46.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723114/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723114/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723114/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-21","Peacekeeping Operations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent assessment he has made of the progress of all current military operations by sea, land and air; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","71590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723115","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-26","<p>The requested information is published in the Department's monthly Service personnel statistics, which can be found at the following link:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/uk-armed-forces-monthly-service-personnel-statistics-2017</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-26T09:30:47.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723115/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723115/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723115/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-21","Reserve Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the strength of the (a) Army Reserve, (b) Royal Navy Reserve, (c) RAF Reserve and (d) Royal Marines Reserve has been in each year since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Wes Streeting","Ilford North","Wes Streeting","71608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723116","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-26","<p>During spring 2018 the runway at RAF Northolt will close to complete improvements to its sub-structure and replace the runway arrestor beds. The precise dates and length of the closure will be determined during the detailed planning phase, which will take place through 2017 and focus on minimising the operational impact. To release cost information on the project at this stage in the process would prejudice the Department's commercial interests.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-26T10:31:43.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723116/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723116/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723116/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-21","RAF Northolt","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what refurbishment works he plans at RAF Northolt in April 2018; what estimate he has made of the cost of those works; and for how long he plans to close RAF Northolt for those works.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","71589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723117","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-27","<p>As RAF Northolt remains a core RAF Station, there are no plans to consult residents on its future.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-27T08:12:43.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723117/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723117/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723117/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-21","RAF Northolt","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether he plans to consult residents and representative organisations in Harrow on the future of RAF Northolt; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","71574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723118","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-27","<p>There are no plans to increase the number of civilian commercial movements which remain capped at 12,000 movements per year.</p><p>There is no cap on military movements which will fluctuate in line with military requirements.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-04-27T08:11:27.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723118/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723118/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723118/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-21","RAF Northolt","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans he has to allow an increase in the number of (a) civilian and (b) military flight movements at RAF Northolt; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","71575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723119","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-26","<p>Further to my answer of 20 April 2017 to question 70281 I can confirm that there are no plans to grant posthumous awards to non-service personnel as part of the RAF's 100th anniversary commemorations.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-04-26T09:31:26.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723119/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723119/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723119/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-21","World War II: Medals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 20 April 2017 to Question 70281, if he will take steps to grant posthumous awards for (a) Lady MacRobert and (b) other non-service personnel.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","71640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723120","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-04-26","<p>The RAF is rightly proud of its connections with the MacRobert family. Whilst there are no plans to name a Typhoon as &quot;MacRobert Spirit - Not For Self But For Country&quot;, the RAF will be naming a 6 Squadron Typhoon &quot;Sir Roderic&quot; after one of Lady MacRobert's fallen sons who served with the Squadron.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-04-26T09:30:21.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723120/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723120/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723120/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-04-21","Military Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 20 April 2017 to Question 70279, if he will take steps to allow the posthumous naming of a current RAF Typhoon fighter aircraft, MacRobert's Spirit - not for self but for country, after Lady MacRobert in recognition of her philanthropic donation of four fighter aircraft during the Second World War.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","71664"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723121","Department for Education","false","2017-04-26","<p>We have committed over £1 billion more per year by 2019-20 to fund our commitments on the early years entitlements. This includes £300 million per year from 2017-18 for a significant increase to the hourly rate paid to local authorities for delivering the government-funded entitlements, including 30 hours of childcare from September 2017.</p><p>We will require that all local authorities pass 93% in 2017-18 then 95% from 2018-19 of 30 hours childcare funding to providers.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to this, we are also investing £100 million of capital funding to create nearly 18,000 additional places for eligible children to help meet demand from working parents. This funding will support even more providers to deliver 30 hours.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-04-26T16:28:49.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723121/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723121/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723121/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-21","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 19 April 2017 to Question HL6597, on children: day care, how much additional funding will be provided to local authorities and childcare providers to enable them to deliver 30 hours of free childcare from September 2017; and what estimate she has made of the additional places for eligible children that will be created by that funding.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","71641"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723122","Department for Education","false","2017-04-27","<p>It has not proved possible to respond to the hon. Member in the time available before Prorogation.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-04-27T11:11:04.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723122/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723122/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723122/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-21","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much funding was available to schools in England in each year since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Wes Streeting","Ilford North","Wes Streeting","71606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723123","Department for Education","false","2017-04-26","<p>Local authorities are responsible for making an assessment about the number of 30 hours free childcare places that providers plan to offer in their areas. To support them to deliver 30 hours, the Government is investing £100 million to create almost 18,000 additional early years places for eligible children to help meet demand from working parents. This is backed by £1 billion extra revenue per year for the early years entitlements, including £300 million per year to increase the funding rates paid to nurseries, pre-schools and childminders that choose to deliver the offer. This means that Brighton and Hove local authority will see an increase in their hourly funding rate to £4.45. The Early Years Workforce Strategy published on 3<sup>rd</sup> March, also aims to support the early years sector to remove barriers to attracting, retaining and developing staff.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-04-26T16:29:56.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723123/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723123/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723123/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-21","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the number of (a) nurseries and (b) nursery school places in (i) Brighton Pavilion constituency, (ii) Brighton and Hove local authority area that will offer 30 hours of free childcare from September 2017; whether there is sufficient (A) funding and (B) staffing capacity in place to meet demand for such places; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","71555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723124","Department for Education","false","2017-04-27","<p>It has not proved possible to respond to the hon. Member in the time available before Prorogation.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-04-27T11:10:52.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723124/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723124/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723124/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-21","Class Sizes: Bristol","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the average class size is in primary schools in Bristol; and how many primary school classes in Bristol have more than 30 pupils.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","71549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723125","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-26","<p>The UK remains a member of the EU until we leave, with full rights and obligations of membership. Defra officials are currently examining the proposed Large Combustion Plant Best Available Techniques Reference Document ahead of the vote later this week.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-04-26T09:45:37.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723125/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723125/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723125/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-21","Fossil Fuelled Power Stations: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if the Government will vote in support of the EU's revised Best Available Techniques Reference Document for Large Combustion Plants at the European Industrial Emissions Directive Article 75 Committee on 28 April 2017.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","71548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723126","Department of Health","false","2017-04-27","<p>The Food Standards Agency has the following data on numbers of equines slaughtered in approved premises in England. There were no operating equine slaughter premises in Wales during the year 2016.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Type of CCTV in slaughterhouse</p></td><td><p>Number of horses slaughtered between 1 January 2016 and 31 December 2016</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>With no CCTV</p></td><td><p>136</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>With no CCTV installed in stunning, killing or bleeding areas</p></td><td><p>3,077</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>With CCTV in all areas</p></td><td><p>115</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-04-27T08:30:19.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723126/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723126/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723126/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-21","Slaughterhouses: Horses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many horses and ponies were slaughtered in UK abattoirs (a) with no CCTV, (b) with no CCTV installed in stunning, killing or bleeding areas and (c) with CCTV in all areas in 2016.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","71576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723127","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-25","<p>In 2015 Defra commissioned an external consultancy to undertake economic analysis and research into various aspects of the operation of the market for packaging waste recovery notes (PRN). This included work that examined certain aspects of competition between compliance schemes. The final reports will be published in due course.</p><p> </p><p>No formal assessment has been made of introducing a single compliance scheme system.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-04-25T14:25:13.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723127/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723127/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723127/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-21","Packaging: Waste Disposal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the level of competition between compliance schemes for the Producer Responsibility Obligations (Packaging Waste) Regulations; and what consideration has she given to the effect of introducing a single compliance scheme.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","71528"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723128","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-26","<p>In February 2015, the Farm Animal Welfare Committee (FAWC) published an independent assessment of the use of CCTV in slaughterhouses which concluded that CCTV can offer real benefits, particularly to slaughterhouse operators, but that it cannot replace the need for businesses to have proper monitoring procedures in place.</p><p> </p><p>The vast majority of horses are slaughtered in slaughterhouses in England which have CCTV installed for welfare purposes, although cameras may not be present in all areas. Official Veterinarians also have the power to seize CCTV footage if they suspect that welfare standards are not being met.</p><p> </p><p>Defra continues to encourage slaughterhouses to install CCTV in all areas on a voluntary basis in order to realise the benefits to animal welfare set out in the FAWC report.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-04-26T11:38:25.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723128/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723128/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723128/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-21","Slaughterhouses: CCTV","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to encourage voluntary take-up of CCTV in equine slaughterhouses.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","71648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723129","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>​The UK has received no formal requests for assistance under the Article X provisions. However, in the last three years we have contributed to the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons' programme to provide training assistance for States Parties in East Africa and South East Asia. The UK also assisted with the production of a treatment guide for victims of chemical weapons which was published in 2015. These activities were funded over and above our assessed contributions to the OPCW.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-04-26T11:32:29.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723129/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723129/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723129/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-21","Chemical Weapons Convention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many requests the Government has received for assistance under Article X of the Chemical Weapons Convention in each year since 2010; from which countries such requests have been received; what the nature was of each such request; and what assistance the Government provided in response to each such request.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","71651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723130","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>​We welcome the Government of Iraq's decision to invite the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) to support its investigations into chemical weapons use in Iraq. Iraq's findings confirmed the use of sulphur mustard in Iraq by a non-State actor in 2015 and 2016. We condemn the use of chemical weapons by anyone anywhere. Those who commit such atrocities must be held accountable. We continue to work with Iraq and other international partners.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-04-26T11:22:54.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723130/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723130/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723130/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-21","Iraq: Chemical Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the progress of the Iraqi authorities in (a) investigating reports of attacks using chemical weapons in that country, (b) establishing responsibility for such attacks and (c) bringing the perpetrators of such attacks to justice.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","71646"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723131","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>All members of the Murder and Manslaughter Team complete the mandatory training for all front line consular staff at the start of their roles. They then complete a further programme of assessed learning specifically designed for those handling murder/manslaughter cases. The team also take opportunities for wider learning and development on trauma and crisis work to ensure they provide the best support to families of those murdered and killed overseas.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-04-26T14:52:14.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723131/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723131/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723131/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-21","Diplomatic Service: Qualifications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the murder and manslaughter teams in Consular Directorates are required to have particular qualifications to handle the cases they deal with; and what training such staff receive to carry out that work.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","71543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723132","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>​​The UK has been at the forefront of those making the case that those found responsible for chemical weapons attacks must be held to account. A UK-US-French attempt to agree UN sanctions in response to previous chemical weapons attacks was vetoed by Russia and China in the UN Security Council on 28 February. In March we helped secure agreement from the EU to add 4 Syrian military officials to the sanctions list for their role in carrying out chemical weapon attacks. We welcome the further sanctions Canada and the US have introduced in recent days. We will continue work with partners to take action against those responsible for chemical weapons attacks.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-04-26T11:29:49.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723132/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723132/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723132/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-21","Syria: Chemical Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what plans the Government has to seek the agreement of the (a) OPCW Executive Council, (b) Conference of States Parties to the Chemical Weapons Convention and (c) UN Security Council on punitive measures against the Government of Syria in the event that the use of chemical weapons by that Government in Khan Sheikhoun on 4 April 2017 is confirmed by the OPCW-UN Joint Investigative Mechanism.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","71566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723133","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>​Monitoring the security situation in the Western Sahara is one of the key responsibilities of the UN Mission for the Referendum in Western Sahara (MINURSO). The Government maintains a close dialogue with MINURSO and with the UN's Department of Peacekeeping Operations in New York. We support the UN Secretary General's calls on both parties to the Western Sahara dispute to exercise restraint and take steps to avoid escalating tensions.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-04-26T10:53:52.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723133/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723133/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723133/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-21","Western Sahara: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the security situation in Western Sahara.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","71531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723134","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","true","2017-04-26","<p><del class="ministerial">​The UK has been at the forefront of those making the case that those found responsible for chemical weapons attacks must be held to account. A UK-US-French attempt to agree UN sanctions in response to previous chemical weapons attacks was vetoed by Russia and China in the UN Security Council on 28 February. In March we helped secure agreement from the EU to add 4 Syrian military officials to the sanctions list for their role in carrying out chemical weapon attacks. We welcome the further sanctions Canada and the US have introduced in recent days. We will continue work with partners to take action against those responsible for chemical weapons attacks. </del><ins class="ministerial">The UK’s priority for the recent session of the OPCW Executive Council was to make clear international condemnation of the 4 April Khan Sheikhoun attack and to confirm our support for the OPCW investigation which began immediately following that attack. We welcome the Executive Council’s overwhelming vote on 20 April to reject a Russian-Iranian proposal which would have distracted from and undermined the OPCW expert investigations which are already under way. We will continue to support the work of the OPCW Fact Finding Mission and the OPCW-UN Joint Investigative Mechanism.</ins></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-04-26T13:30:31.283Z","2017-04-27T15:35:02.887Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723134/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723134/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723134/answer","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723134/answer/previousversion/45979","Biography information for Boris Johnson","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-21","Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the Government's priorities were for the 54th Special Session of the OPCW Executive Council on 13 and 19 April 2017; what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the outcome of those meetings; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","71568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723135","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>​The UN-Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons Joint Investigative Mechanism confirmed last year Daesh responsibility for at least one attack in Syria in 2015 using sulphur mustard. There have been a number of further subsequent alleged uses of chemical weapons by non state actors in Iraq, including in recent weeks. Whether the materials for such attacks were produced at the University of Mosul or elsewhere, such attacks only underline the important of international action to defeat Daesh.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-04-26T11:17:18.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723135/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723135/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723135/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-21","Islamic State: Chemical Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the former capacity of Daesh to produce chemical weapons at the University of Mosul; what assessment he has made of the quantity of chemical weapons produced at that site; what assessment he has made of the quantity of chemical weapons produced at that site; and what assessment he has made of the potential threat posed by the spread of chemical weapons produced at that site.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","71529"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723136","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>​The Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons(OPCW) is responsible for verifying Syria's declaration and its Director General has reported to the Executive Council that despite a significant amount of time and resource devoted to engagement with the Syrian authorities over the last three years, &quot;gaps, inconsistencies and discrepancies remain in the Government of Syria's declaration to the OPCW&quot;. These gaps and continuing attacks mean that the OPCW, with our strong support, continues to investigate Syria's declaration to seek to uncover the full picture.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-04-26T11:25:16.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723136/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723136/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723136/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-21","Syria: Chemical Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what estimate the Government has made of the (a) size of the chemical weapons stockpile and (b) number of chemical weapons production facilities not formally declared to the OPCW by the Government of Syria.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","71567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723137","Department for International Development","false","2017-04-26","<p>The Secretary of State for International Development, the Rt Hon Priti Patel visited South Sudan on 10 April 2017. Severe food insecurity levels and malnutrition rates, including pockets of famine, continue to worsen alongside an unprecedented dry season and cholera outbreak. The operational environment is significantly constrained with severe access issues and diminishing humanitarian space. Fighting continues across the country, causing widespread displacement and driving the humanitarian crisis. There are 7.5 million people in need of humanitarian assistance and over 3 million people displaced.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-04-26T15:36:43.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723137/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723137/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723137/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-04-21","South Sudan: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent assessment she has made of the humanitarian situation in South Sudan.","false","Biography information for Mr Jonathan Lord","Woking","Mr Jonathan Lord","71547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723138","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>​We support the renewal of the mandate of the UN Mission for the Referendum in Western Sahara (MINURSO) and UK officials are discussing the UN Security Council Resolution that does this with Security Council partners. Previous Resolutions have stressed the importance of improving the human rights situation in Western Sahara and the Tindouf camps. We will continue to support efforts to ensure that MINURSO is able to fulfil the mandate given to it by the UN Security Council.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-04-26T10:52:32.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723138/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723138/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723138/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-21","UN Mission for the Referendum in Western Sahara","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the Government's policy is on the potential renewal of the mandate of the UN Mission for the Referendum in Western Sahara; and if he will make representations at the UN Security Council to expand the mandate of that mission to include a requirement to monitor and report on human rights abuses in Western Sahara.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","71534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723139","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>​The Government's priority is that the Khan Sheikhoun attack is investigated and that those responsible are held to account. Once the Fact Finding Mission has determined that chemical weapons have or have likely been used in Syria, it is for the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons-UN Joint Investigative Mechanism to seek to attribute responsibility. We will work with partners to support that process.</p><p>The OPCW Executive Council met in special session on 13, 19 and 20 April to discuss the response to the Khan Sheikhoun attack and we will consider whether a further meeting of the Executive Council could usefully support that process.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-04-26T13:32:06.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723139/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723139/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723139/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-21","Syria: Chemical Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he plans for the OPCW Executive Council to convene in Special Session when the Fact finding Mission in Syria completes its investigation of the attack of 4 April 2017 in Khan Sheikhoun; and what priorities the Government has planned for such a meeting in the event that the use of chemical weapons in the attack is confirmed by the Fact Finding Mission.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","71570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723140","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>​In March 2017, the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons Executive Council agreed an approach proposed by Iraq to dealing with the remaining remnants of Saddam-era chemical weapons programme remaining in bunkers at Al-Muthanna in Iraq. We understand that the remaining materials are in poor condition which makes them hazardous to access and handle. However we continue to press the Government of Iraq to proceed as swiftly as possible and to ensure the security of the site.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-04-26T11:05:48.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723140/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723140/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723140/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-21","Iraq: Chemical Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the progress of the Iraqi Government in implementing its plans for the destruction of remnants of chemical weapons stored at the Al-Muthanna complex; what assessment he has made of the security situation at that complex; and what assessment he has made of the potential threat posed by the spread of chemical weapons stored at that complex.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","71535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723141","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>The UK is deeply concerned by the continuing violence in many parts of the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC). We frequently raise the issue with the Government of DRC who are ultimately responsible for providing security for their citizens. We also recognise the need for the UN peacekeeping mission (MONUSCO) to deliver more, especially since its mandate was renewed in March. We have pushed hard in the UN Security Council for the protection of civilians to be the mission’s first priority. A growing body of evidence implicates elements of the Congolese security services in killings and other human rights violations. We have made clear that those who commit such violations, will face consequences for their actions. EU sanctions are currently being considered.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-04-26T15:12:55.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723141/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723141/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723141/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-21","Democratic Republic of Congo: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the security situation in the Democratic Republic of Congo.","false","Biography information for Mr Jonathan Lord","Woking","Mr Jonathan Lord","71546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723142","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>​It is the responsibility of the Government of Iraq to investigate alleged use of chemical weapons on its territory. At Iraqi request, and in accordance with the Chemical Weapons Convention, the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons has provided assistance to the Iraqi authorities over the past two years to support their investigation into such allegations. We therefore judge there is no requirement for the establishment of any additional international mechanism to investigate attacks using chemical weapons in Iraq.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-04-26T11:45:58.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723142/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723142/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723142/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-21","Iraq: Chemical Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the Government's policy is on the establishment of an independent international mechanism to investigate attacks using chemical weapons in Iraq.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","71536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723143","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>​I refer the Hon. Member to my response to written question 70842, and the answers I gave when replying to an Urgent Question in the House on 20 April 2017.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-04-26T15:45:31.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723143/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723143/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723143/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-21","Chechnya: Homosexuality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking in response to reports of the imprisonment and abuse of homosexual men in Chechnya.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","71594"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723144","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>The FCO does not record the volume of British citizens living abroad. The United Nations in their report on <em>'Trends in International Migrant Stock: Migrants by Destination and Origin' </em>estimated in 2015 that 4,917,460 British citizens were living outside of the UK. The report can be found at <a href="http://www.un.org/en/development/desa/population/migration/data/estimates2/estimates15.shtml" target="_blank">http://www.un.org/en/development/desa/population/migration/data/estimates2/estimates15.shtml</a>.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-04-26T14:53:59.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723144/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723144/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723144/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-21","British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many British citizens are estimated to be living abroad, by country.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","71595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723145","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>​We have six Consular Regional Directors in our overseas network providing strategic leadership to our front line consular services around the world. They are based in the Netherlands, Oman, Singapore, South Africa, Spain and the USA at a total cost of £761,349 per annum.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-04-26T14:47:24.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723145/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723145/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723145/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-21","Diplomatic Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many non-frontline UK-based Consular Regional Directors are based overseas; in which countries those directors are based; and what the total cost is of those posts.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","71588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723146","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>I met with Sri Lankan Foreign Minister Samaraweera at the UN Human Rights Council in Geneva on 28 February. I also wrote to both the Foreign Minister and Prime Minister Ranil Wickremesinghe on 20 April. In the meeting and subsequent letters, I recognised the Sri Lankan government's efforts to improve the human rights situation in Sri Lanka. I also welcomed their co-sponsorship of UN Human Rights Council Resolution 34/1. I encouraged accelerated progress towards fulfilling the commitments their government made in co-sponsoring Resolution 34/1 and raised the importance of the return of all military-held private land, the delivery of devolution through constitutional reform, the establishment of credible transitional justice mechanisms and the development of new counter-terrorism legislation in line with international human rights standards.</p><p>The UK is committed to the full implementation of Resolution 34/1 and will continue to support the Government of Sri Lanka in its efforts to promote reconciliation and human rights.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-04-26T09:01:28.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723146/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723146/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723146/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-21","Sri Lanka: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he is having with his counterpart in Sri Lanka on implementation of UN Human Rights Council resolutions relating to human rights in Sri Lanka.","false","Biography information for Wes Streeting","Ilford North","Wes Streeting","71609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723147","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>​There have been a number of credible reports of use of chemical weapons in Iraq since 2014, becoming more frequent over time. We welcome the Government of Iraq's decision to invite the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons to support its investigations into chemical weapons use in Iraq. The Government of Iraq's findings confirmed the use of sulphur mustard in northern Iraq by a non-State actor in 2015 and 2016 and investigations continue into other allegations of use.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-04-26T11:03:34.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723147/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723147/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723147/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-21","Iraq: Chemical Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent reports he has received of attacks using chemical weapons in Iraq; what estimate he has made of the number of such attacks during (a) 2014, (b) 2015, (c) 2016 and (d) 2017; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","71622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723148","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>The UK made voluntary financial contributions to the Syria Trust Fund of £276,000 in 2014-15 and £50,000 in 2016-17. We have also supported significant contributions from the European Union, including 2.3 million euros announced in March 2016. The UK has not contributed to the other two funds over this period.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-04-26T11:34:43.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723148/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723148/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723148/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-21","Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what voluntary financial contributions the Government made to the (a) Organisation for the Prevention of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) Syria Trust Fund, (b) OPCW Voluntary Fund for Assistance and (c) voluntary trust fund for the OPCW International Support Network for Victims of Chemical Weapons in (i) 2014-15, (ii) 2015-16 and (iii) 2016-17, in addition to the UK's assessed contributions to the OPCW budget, in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","71623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723149","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>I am not aware of any current funding shortfall in these funds.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-04-26T11:33:16.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723149/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723149/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723149/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-21","Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what information his Department holds on the current funding shortfall of the (a) Organisation for the Prevention of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) Syria Trust Fund, (b) OPCW Voluntary Fund for Assistance and (c) voluntary trust fund for the OPCW International Support Network for Victims of Chemical Weapons.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","71624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723150","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>​It is for the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) to judge whether they are being provided with adequate access. The OPCW Director General has previously been clear in his criticism of Syrian co-operation with the OPCW over the Syrian chemical weapons declarations, in July 2016 calling on Syria &quot;to provide information that is scientifically and technically plausible, to facilitate access to individuals with strategic knowledge and oversight of the Syrian chemical weapons programme, and to engage in a dialogue that is proactive and fully transparent&quot;. We continue to call on Syria to co-operate fully, including with the investigation into the Khan Sheikhoun attack. The Director General said on 19 April that he anticipated that the investigation would complete a first report of its findings within two weeks.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-04-26T11:01:42.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723150/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723150/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723150/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-21","Syria: Chemical Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the Organisation for the Prevention of Chemical Weapons Fact Finding Mission in Syria is being provided with adequate access to relevant (a) sites, (b) records and (c) personnel to carry out its investigations of the attack of 4 April 2017 in Khan Sheikhoun; and when he expects that investigation to conclude.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","71625"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723151","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>The safety and security of staff conducting investigations is the responsibility of the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) and the Joint Investigative Mechanism working with UN Department of Safety and Security, and of states in which they are operating. In his statement on 19 April, the OPCW Director General underlined the importance he attaches to ensuring the investigators' safety and security.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-04-26T10:59:39.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723151/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723151/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723151/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-21","Syria: Chemical Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether adequate steps are being taken to protect the security of personnel from the (a) Organisation for the Prevention of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) Fact Finding Mission and (b) OPCW-UN Joint Investigative Mechanism deployed in Syria.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","71626"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723152","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>​The UK has strongly supported the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) and UN investigations from the outset of their work. In addition to financial contributions, the UK has provided support in the UN Security Council and OPCW Executive Council for their establishment, operation and for action on their conclusions.</p><p>In response to the OPCW's request to all states to provide assistance and information, we have helped train inspectors in forensic interviewing and negotiating skills, shared information we have on the attacks they are investigating and lobbied other states to be similarly supportive.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-04-26T10:49:15.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723152/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723152/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723152/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-21","Syria: Chemical Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to support the work of the (a) Organisation for the Prevention of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) Fact Finding Mission in Syria and (b) UN-OPCW Joint Investigative Mechanism for Syria in addition to the UK's financial contributions to the OPCW budget.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","71627"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723153","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>Substantial chemical weapons stocks have been removed from Syria and destroyed following the agreement reached in 2013. However, the actions of the Syrian regime have shown that it retained some weapons and failed to abide by the obligations it took on when joining the Chemical Weapons Convention.</p><p>As I said to the House on 18 April, the deal was no substitute for resolute action. The UK continues to promote a clear and united international community approach to put an end to the possession and use of chemical weapons by the Syrian regime.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-04-26T10:45:31.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723153/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723153/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723153/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-04-21","Syria: Chemical Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to his oral contribution of 18 April 2017, Official Report, column 551, when the Government decided that the Framework for Elimination of Syrian Chemical Weapons, agreed between the US and Russia on 14 September 2013, was the result of a misjudgement; whether that decision has also been reached by the US Administration; and what assessment he has made of the implications of that decision for the prospects of removing the remaining stockpiles of chemical weapons from Syria.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","71642"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723154","Department of Health","false","2017-04-27","<p>Data on costs is not available in the format requested. However the health costs associated with alcohol misuse are estimated to cost the National Health Service in England around £3.5 billion each year and the latest estimate of the cost to the NHS in England of overweight or obesity related ill-health is £5.1 billion each year.</p><p> </p><p>Data is not available by cause of condition to provide an expenditure estimate requested for viral hepatitis.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-04-27T08:35:51.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723154/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723154/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723154/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-21","Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate his Department has made of the costs to the NHS and social care system of treatment for (a) alcohol abuse, (b) obesity and (c) viral hepatitis in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Flick Drummond","Portsmouth South","Mrs Flick Drummond","71657"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723155","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>Taxation policy is a matter for the Chancellor of the Exchequer; the United Kingdom Government believes alcohol duties should be proportional to alcohol content. A consultation on the introduction of a new band to target, high strength ‘white’ ciders is underway and ends on 12 June.</p><p> </p><p>No estimate has currently been made of the effect of a possible new duty band on health.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-04-26T12:39:14.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723155/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723155/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723155/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-21","Cider: Health Hazards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the potential effect of a new duty band for super-strength cider on health outcomes.","false","Biography information for Mrs Flick Drummond","Portsmouth South","Mrs Flick Drummond","71658"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723156","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>The Care Quality Commission (CQC) is the independent regulator of health and adult social care. All providers of regulated activities, including National Health Service and independent providers, have to register with the CQC and follow a set of fundamental standards of safety and quality below which care should never fall. The fundamental standards describe the basic requirements that providers should always meet, and outline the outcomes that services users should always expect.</p><p> </p><p>The CQC inspects providers against the fundamental standards and publishes the results on its website to help people choose care.</p><p> </p><p>The CQC has provided the following information:</p><p> </p><p>Number of Care Homes with an Overall Rating of Inadequate or Requires Improvement Published Between 1 October 2014 and 31 March 2017</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="4"><p>Number of Care homes</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Nursing Home</p></td><td><p>Nursing Home</p></td><td><p>Residential Home</p></td><td><p>Residential Home</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Financial Year Rating Published</p></td><td><p>Requires improvement</p></td><td><p>Inadequate</p></td><td><p>Requires improvement</p></td><td><p>Inadequate</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1 October 2014 - 31 March 15</p></td><td><p>341</p></td><td><p>97</p></td><td><p>383</p></td><td><p>101</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>1,309</p></td><td><p>271</p></td><td><p>1,988</p></td><td><p>309</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>1,241</p></td><td><p>260</p></td><td><p>1,927</p></td><td><p>306</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: CQC database as at 3 April 2017</p><p> </p><p>Notes: Some Nursing Homes or Residential Homes may have received two or more overall ratings since 1 October 2014. The above figures show the number of ratings published and include care homes which are no longer active. The above figures should not be used as an indication of total number of care homes currently rated Requires Improvement and Inadequate. The CQC began rating Adult Social Care providers in October 2014.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","71655","2017-04-26T14:33:26.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723156/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723156/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723156/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-21","Care Homes: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many residential care homes have been rated by the Care Quality Commission as (a) inadequate or (b) requires improvement in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","71654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723157","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>The Care Quality Commission (CQC) is the independent regulator of health and adult social care. All providers of regulated activities, including National Health Service and independent providers, have to register with the CQC and follow a set of fundamental standards of safety and quality below which care should never fall. The fundamental standards describe the basic requirements that providers should always meet, and outline the outcomes that services users should always expect.</p><p> </p><p>The CQC inspects providers against the fundamental standards and publishes the results on its website to help people choose care.</p><p> </p><p>The CQC has provided the following information:</p><p> </p><p>Number of Care Homes with an Overall Rating of Inadequate or Requires Improvement Published Between 1 October 2014 and 31 March 2017</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="4"><p>Number of Care homes</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Nursing Home</p></td><td><p>Nursing Home</p></td><td><p>Residential Home</p></td><td><p>Residential Home</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Financial Year Rating Published</p></td><td><p>Requires improvement</p></td><td><p>Inadequate</p></td><td><p>Requires improvement</p></td><td><p>Inadequate</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1 October 2014 - 31 March 15</p></td><td><p>341</p></td><td><p>97</p></td><td><p>383</p></td><td><p>101</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>1,309</p></td><td><p>271</p></td><td><p>1,988</p></td><td><p>309</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>1,241</p></td><td><p>260</p></td><td><p>1,927</p></td><td><p>306</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: CQC database as at 3 April 2017</p><p> </p><p>Notes: Some Nursing Homes or Residential Homes may have received two or more overall ratings since 1 October 2014. The above figures show the number of ratings published and include care homes which are no longer active. The above figures should not be used as an indication of total number of care homes currently rated Requires Improvement and Inadequate. The CQC began rating Adult Social Care providers in October 2014.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","71654","2017-04-26T14:33:26.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723157/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723157/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723157/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-21","Care Homes: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many nursing homes have been rated by the Care Quality Commission as (a) inadequate or (b) requires improvement in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","71655"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723158","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>The two-week wait standard for non-urgent referral for breast symptoms has not been removed. In February 2017, 93.8% of people referred by a general practitioner for investigation of breast symptoms were seen by a specialist within two weeks.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-04-26T10:08:52.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723158/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723158/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723158/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-21","Breast Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the effect on patient experience of the removal of the two-week wait target for non-urgent referral for breast cancer symptoms.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","71586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723159","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>This information is not held centrally. National Health Service commissioners and providers work together to ensure that local people receive a full range of services that meet their needs.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-04-26T15:55:22.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723159/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723159/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723159/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-21","Accident and Emergency Departments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many accident and emergency departments have been (a) closed and (b) downgraded in each year since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Wes Streeting","Ilford North","Wes Streeting","71607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723160","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>Clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) are responsible for commissioning local health services and ensuring the needs of the local health population are met. NHS England is responsible for oversight of the commissioning system. National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) guidelines are evidence based best practice for clinicians but are not mandatory.</p><p> </p><p>I have written to NHS England specifically asking that it re-emphasise to all those involved in commissioning fertility services that they should have regard to the NICE fertility guidelines. In the light of the response to that letter, the Department will consider what further action may be appropriate.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England and professional and stakeholder groups including the Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority, are working together to develop commissioning guidance. This guidance aims to improve the quality of commissioning and further encourage the implementation of the NICE fertility guidelines. NHS England has agreed to disseminate and promote the commissioning guidance to all CCGs in England.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","71544","2017-04-26T09:42:24.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723160/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723160/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723160/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-21","In Vitro Fertilisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will take steps to ensure that NICE guidelines for IVF treatment are fully implemented in the NHS.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","71611"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723161","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>The Care Quality Commission (CQC) is the independent regulator of health and adult social care in England. The CQC has provided the following information in the attached table.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-04-26T14:57:07.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723161/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723161/answer","PQ71599 - Number of active care homes and number of care home beds.docx","PQ71599 - Number of active care homes and number of care home beds.docx","PQ71599 attached table","PQ71599 attached table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723161/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-21","Care Homes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many (a) registered care home and (b) nursing home places there were in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","71599"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723162","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>Spending on Child and Adolescent Mental Health Services (CAMHS) was reported separately in the Mental Health Five Year Forward View Dashboard from 2016/17 and is not available for previous years in this format.</p><p> </p><p>The Dashboard reported that clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) on CAMHS cash spend per head in 2016/17 plans across CCGs was an average of £46.71. This figure does not include spend on Specialised CAMHS services.</p><p> </p><p>Figures from NHS England’s Five Year Forward View Dashboard report that clinical commissioning groups cash spend on mental health per head of the population in £164.68 in 2016/17 and 2015/16 was £159.58.</p><p> </p><p>Spending on per head of the population for previous years is not available in this format.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","71596","2017-04-26T16:30:10.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723162/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723162/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723162/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-21","Mental Health Services: Per Capita Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much was spent in (a) cash and (b) real terms on mental health services per head of population in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","71598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723163","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>Spending on Child and Adolescent Mental Health Services (CAMHS) was reported separately in the Mental Health Five Year Forward View Dashboard from 2016/17 and is not available for previous years in this format.</p><p> </p><p>The Dashboard reported that clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) on CAMHS cash spend per head in 2016/17 plans across CCGs was an average of £46.71. This figure does not include spend on Specialised CAMHS services.</p><p> </p><p>Figures from NHS England’s Five Year Forward View Dashboard report that clinical commissioning groups cash spend on mental health per head of the population in £164.68 in 2016/17 and 2015/16 was £159.58.</p><p> </p><p>Spending on per head of the population for previous years is not available in this format.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","71598","2017-04-26T16:30:10.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723163/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723163/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723163/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-21","Mental Health Services: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much was spent in (a) cash and (b) real terms on child and adolescent mental health services for each young person receiving such services in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","71596"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723164","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>There are two Cancer Alliances across the Frimley Sustainability and Transformation Plan footprint. Representatives of the Sustainability and Transformation Plan are included in the membership of each newly formed Cancer Alliance Board, which give strategic direction on behalf of the Sustainability and Transformation Plan and receive assurance and advice on priority setting and delivery of cancer services.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-04-26T14:34:45.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723164/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723164/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723164/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-21","Cancer: Frimley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to ensure clear strategic governance in the delivery of cancer services with the Frimley Health Sustainability and Transformation Plan.","false","Biography information for Michael Gove","Surrey Heath","Michael Gove","71610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723165","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>The attached table shows counts of finished admission episodes with an emergency admission from a care home from 2009-10 to 2015-16. It is likely that the ‘emergency admissions from care homes’ total figures are incomplete and therefore significantly understated because some relevant admissions may have been coded under ‘usual place of residence’.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-04-26T14:45:45.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723165/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723165/answer","PQ71597 attached document.docx","PQ71597 attached document.docx","PQ71597 attached document","PQ71597 attached document","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723165/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-21","Hospitals: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many patients were admitted to hospital from a care home as an emergency admission in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","71597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723166","Department of Health","false","2017-04-27","<p>Based upon available diary evidence, there are no records of Ministers having specifically met with the Epsom and St Helier NHS Trust to discuss the future of St Helier Hospital.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-04-27T08:34:00.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723166/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723166/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723166/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-21","St Helier Hospital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when Ministers in his Department last discussed the future of St Helier Hospital with the Epsom and St Helier NHS Trust.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","71613"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723167","Department of Health","false","2017-04-27","<p>The Department and the Secretary of State have regular discussions with the British Medical Association and hospital trusts on a range of issues.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State has always made clear that European Union nationals who work in the National Health Service make a valuable contribution and securing their futures will be a priority in the Brexit negotiations.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-04-27T08:33:13.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723167/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723167/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723167/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-21","Doctors: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions his Department has had with (a) Hospital Trusts and (b) the British Medical Association on the effect of the UK leaving the EU on the number of doctors from the EU working in the NHS.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","71614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723168","Department of Health","false","2017-04-27","<p>The Department and the Secretary of State have regular discussions with the Royal College of Nursing and hospital trusts on a range of issues.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State has always made clear that European Union nationals who work in the National Health Service make a valuable contribution and securing their futures will be a priority in the Brexit negotiations.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-04-27T08:35:00.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723168/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723168/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723168/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-21","Nurses: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent discussions his Department has had with (a) Hospital Trusts and (b) the Royal College of Nursing on the effect of the UK leaving the EU on the number of nursing staff from the EU working in the NHS.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","71615"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723169","Department of Health","false","2017-04-27","<p>The conditions applicable to any grants awarded to sexual health charities are set out in the grant award letters, including a specific clause stating that the award has been made under the provisions of Section 64 and may not be used for lobbying. Any underspend is also required to be reported and returned to the Department.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-04-27T08:31:38.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723169/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723169/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723169/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-21","Health Education: Sex","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether funding given to sexual health charities is ring-fenced so that it is only spent on service provision and not on lobbying activities; and how his Department ensures surpluses that are made from services are not used for lobbying.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","71537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723170","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>The Department does not directly fund services that provide advice on unplanned or crisis pregnancies. The Government’s Framework for Sexual Health Improvement in England (2013) sets out that women considering an abortion should be referred or signposted to services which provide impartial, accurate information and, if required, counselling on the full range of options available to women.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","71538","2017-04-26T15:03:20.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723170/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723170/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723170/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-21","Abortion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much his Department has spent on services targeted at offering alternatives to abortion for women with crisis pregnancies in each of the last five years; and on what those funds were spent.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","71552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723171","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>NHS England has initiated a Neurology Advisory Group, with the purpose of seeking alignment between programmes in NHS England, the other health Arm’s Length Bodies and system partners, including the Chief Executive of Parkinson’s UK, relevant to people with neurological conditions. The group has acknowledged that data from the NHS GP survey has consistently indicated that people with Neurological Conditions have the highest levels of anxiety and depression. This is an important issue and we are working with the Neurological Alliance who are due to publish a report on Mental Health and Neurological conditions in early summer. The Neurology Advisory Group will ensure that there is system alignment and a national approach to any recommendations, which will be of benefit to patients.</p><p> </p><p>As set out in Implementing the Five Year Forward View for Mental Health the expansion of Improving Access to Psychological Therapies services will focus on people with long term conditions or medically unexplained symptoms. New psychological therapy provision will see physical and mental health care provision co-located. Therapy will be integrated into existing medical pathways and services – either primary care, or secondary care services including Neurology.</p><p> </p><p>The report can be viewed here:</p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/mental-health/taskforce/imp/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/mental-health/taskforce/imp/</a></p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","71559","2017-04-26T12:28:44.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723171/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723171/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723171/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-21","Mental Health Services: Parkinson's Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what barriers to accessing mental health services his Department has identified for people with Parkinson's disease.","false","Biography information for Nick Thomas-Symonds","Torfaen","Nick Thomas-Symonds","71557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723172","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>The information requested is not held.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","71560","2017-04-26T12:25:59.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723172/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723172/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723172/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-21","Mental Health Services: Parkinson's Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people with Parkinson's disease experiencing mental health problems accessed mental health services in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Nick Thomas-Symonds","Torfaen","Nick Thomas-Symonds","71558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723173","Department of Health","false","2017-04-26","<p>NHS England has initiated a Neurology Advisory Group, with the purpose of seeking alignment between programmes in NHS England, the other health Arm’s Length Bodies and system partners, including the Chief Executive of Parkinson’s UK, relevant to people with neurological conditions. The group has acknowledged that data from the NHS GP survey has consistently indicated that people with Neurological Conditions have the highest levels of anxiety and depression. This is an important issue and we are working with the Neurological Alliance who are due to publish a report on Mental Health and Neurological conditions in early summer. The Neurology Advisory Group will ensure that there is system alignment and a national approach to any recommendations, which will be of benefit to patients.</p><p> </p><p>As set out in Implementing the Five Year Forward View for Mental Health the expansion of Improving Access to Psychological Therapies services will focus on people with long term conditions or medically unexplained symptoms. New psychological therapy provision will see physical and mental health care provision co-located. Therapy will be integrated into existing medical pathways and services – either primary care, or secondary care services including Neurology.</p><p> </p><p>The report can be viewed here:</p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/mental-health/taskforce/imp/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/mental-health/taskforce/imp/</a></p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","71557","2017-04-26T12:28:44.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723173/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723173/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/723173/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-04-21","Mental Health Services: Parkinson's Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of mental health support available for people with Parkinson's disease.","false","Biography information for Nick Thomas-Symonds","Torfaen","Nick Thomas-Symonds","71559"
